1 Introduction to Git and GitHub


1.1 What is Git?


- Git is an opensource version control system designed to handle small or large projects. It is usually used by programmers to develop softwares collaboratively while controlling for the source code.
- It is usually implemented using a set of command line tools.

1.1.1 Why use version control?


- It provides a framework for collaborating.
- Allows to track changes to files over time!
- Also, allows to restore previous versions of a file.

1.2 GitHub


- It is one of the many websites which can host your repositories using Git.



2 Working with GitHub

2.1 Github terminology

1. Repository = Directory
- This refers to any directory managed by Git.
- There can be multiple copies of a repository at different locations.
- Files in a repository are tracked by Git which means that they are under version control.


2. Commits = Revision - These are snapshots which record the current state of a tracked file in a repository.
- Commits usually are accompanied with a brief message describing the changes made.
- Make the commit message informative!

Source: https://xkcd.com/1296/


3. Fork = Personal copy of someone elses repository
- This allows you to use and modify someone elses code without affecting the original repository.
- The forked repository is still connected to the original repository. Any changes in the original repository can be synced.

When forking a repository, it will have the same accessibility setting as the original repo. E.g.; forking a private repo will make a private fork, making it public will severe the connection!

4. Push = Update committed changes to the remote repository on GitHub.com
- Locally made changes can be committed and pushed to an online repository.
- This can allow others to access these changes.

5. Pull = Update your local copy with changes made to the remote repository.
- This is especially helpful when you are working collaboratively on a project.
- Also used when youve forked a repository and changes are made to the original repository.

6. Branch = Parallel but different version of a repository.
- Changes in made in the branch dont affect the files in the main/primary branch.

7. Merge = Allows the changes in one branch to be synced with another branch.
- After making changes to a branch, the changes can be merged with the main or any other branch.

8. Pull request = Proposed changes to a repository.
- Pull requests are accepted/rejected by other users working collaboratively in a repository.

9. Stage = Prepare to push changes on git.
- Make sure you review each file before staging it!

2.2 The workflow


Make changes > Stage > Commit > Push

The Git workflow

2.3 What does/doesnt go on GitHub?

2.3.1 What shouldnt be on GitHub:

  • Data files
  • Patient identifiers
  • Passwords/credentials
  • Anything you dont want other people to see

2.3.2 What should go on GitHub

  • Periodic updates to files/repos you are currently working on.
  • .gitignore file! - helps keep certain file types off of GitHub.
Example of a .gitignore file

3 GitKraken

  • Helps simplify Git!
  • It is free and theres a desktop and web version of it. (I have only used the desktop version).
  • Helps you visualize the changes made to each file before staging them!
  • Although GitKraken allows you to edit files, PLEASE dont use it for that purpose.
  • GitKraken help documents - https://help.gitkraken.com/gitkraken-desktop/guide/
